<HEAD>Most Comprehensive Survey Of Milky Way Galaxy To Start Thursday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The most detailed survey of the Milky Way
will start <DATE>Thursday</DATE> at the world's most sensitive radio telescope,
an array of 27 dish-shaped antennas spread across <LOCATION>New Mexico</LOCATION>'s
desert.
   ``Without a doubt this will give us the most comprehensive
picture of our galaxy yet obtained in any kind of wavelength,''
including visible light and radio and infrared radiation, said
<PERSON>Robert H. Becker</PERSON>, associate professor of astronomy at the
<ORGANIZATION>University of California</ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON>Davis</PERSON>.
   The <MONEY>$1 million</MONEY>, two-year survey will be conducted by <PERSON>Becker</PERSON> and
astronomer <PERSON>David Helfand</PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION>Columbia University</ORGANIZATION>. They will use the
Very Large Array radio telescope, a set of 27 antenna dishes, each
about 80 feet in diameter, that move on 20 miles of tracks west of
Socorro, <LOCATION>N.M.</LOCATION>
   The telescope, which started operations in the late <DATE>1970s</DATE>, can
detect fainter radio signals than any other radio telescope, <PERSON>Becker</PERSON>
said <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> during a telephone interview.
   More complete surveys of the heavens beyond our galaxy have been
conducted using powerful optical and infrared telescopes aimed to
look above or below the Milky Way's flattened disk.
   But such telescopes can't survey our own galaxy very well
because visible light is blocked by tremendous amounts of dust
between the <ORGANIZATION>Milky Way</ORGANIZATION>'s stars and because the galaxy is so full of
infrared light sources that it's hard to distinguish various
objects, <PERSON>Becker</PERSON> said.
   The survey will construct maps of the <PERCENT>70 percent</PERCENT> of the Milky
Way visible from the <LOCATION>Northern Hemisphere</LOCATION> by detecting objects that
emit radio waves, which penetrate the dust.
   Such objects include supernovas, or dying, exploding stars; vast
dust-and-gas clouds where new stars are born; and very dense
supernova remnants called neutron stars, pulsars and black holes.
   ``What this kind of survey can do is give you the overall
picture,'' <PERSON>Becker</PERSON> said. ``Until you catalog the contents of your
own galaxy, you're never going to have a clear picture of what the
galaxy is.''
   The disk-shaped Milky Way contains an estimated 100 billion
stars clumped in spiraling arms that stretch across 100,000 light
years, or about 588,000 trillion miles, of space. Earth is located
roughly 22,000 light years, or 130,000 trillion miles, from the
galaxy's center.
   Becker said the survey undoubtedly will produce unexpected
discoveries, but also could help astronomers determine the
frequency and location of supernova explosions invisible to optical
telescopes.
   Shock waves from such explosions are thought to compress gas and
dust to create new stars.
   The survey will help determine if that theory is correct by
showing if there is a link between the location of supernovas and
regions of star formation, <PERSON>Becker</PERSON> said.
   While some stars leave nothing behind after they explode as
supernovas, other supernovas collapse into dense neutron stars,
rotating neutron stars called pulsars or even more dense objects
called black holes, which have gravity so intense that not even
light escapes.
   Becker said the survey should help astronomers learn what
proportion of supernovas become neutron stars, pulsars or black
holes because such objects generate radio signals.
   While the survey won't detect life that might exist elsewhere in
the galaxy, it could help scientists improve estimates of the odds
that such life exists, <PERSON>Becker</PERSON> said.
   ``If one wants to estimate the probability of finding
intelligent life elsewhere in our galaxy, you have to know what the
environment of our galaxy is,'' including the number of objects
that may be orbited by inhabited planets, he said.
   Recent improvements to the <ORGANIZATION>Very Large Array</ORGANIZATION> gave it a much
larger field of view, so ``it will take fewer pointings of the
telescope to map out the Milky Way,'' <PERSON>Becker</PERSON> said.
   Becker and <PERSON>Helfand</PERSON> will have 300 hours of viewing time during
the survey. They then will spend another year or two using
computers to contruct maps using the detected radio signals.
   The first 20 to 24 hours of survey-related observations will
start <DATE>Thursday</DATE> and end <DATE>Saturday</DATE>, with more intermittent
observations regularly scheduled during the next two years each
time the antennas are re-aimed, <PERSON>Becker</PERSON> said.
   The survey is financed by the <ORGANIZATION>University of California</ORGANIZATION>, the
<ORGANIZATION>National Science Foundation</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Lawrence Livermore National
Laboratory</ORGANIZATION>.

</TEXT>
