<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO:  Some astronomers are delighted and awed by discoveries made by
the telescope, despite its fuzzy vision.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  US; SPACE; VEHICLE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Despite a flaw that gives the Hubble Space Telescope a fuzzy view of the
heavens, some astronomers are delighted and awed by discoveries made by the
$1.5 billion craft.;    Researchers said Wednesday that instruments on the
Hubble have found what may be the most massive star ever analyzed, taken the
first step toward a precise measure of the universe and found a large star
that may be about to explode.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  General News  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  FLAWED HUBBLE STILL PRODUCING
TELESCOPE SPOTS MASSIVE STAR, STARTS MEASURE
OF UNIVERSE  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     But scientists at the <ORGANIZATION>American Astronomical Society</ORGANIZATION> meeting here said the
Hubble must be repaired to get its full scientific value. One researcher said
about <PERCENT>80 percent</PERCENT> of his studies had been canceled because of the telescope's
problems.;    <ORGANIZATION>Hubble</ORGANIZATION> was launched in <DATE>April</DATE> and engineers later discovered that
a mirror on the telescope was ground to the wrong prescription, giving a
slightly out-of-focus view.;    The flaw, however, has little effect on a
Hubble instrument called the high resolution spectrograph. And <PERSON>Sally Heap</PERSON>, a
<ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> astronomer, said the instrument has studied the most massive star ever
measured precisely.;    <PERSON>Heap</PERSON> said the star, called <PERSON>Melnick</PERSON> 42, is about 100
times larger than the <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>'s sun and shines about a million times brighter.; 
  Every 100,000 years, she said, <PERSON>Melnick</PERSON> 42 boils away gas with a mass equal
to the sun, creating a "stellar wind" that moves away at more than 6 million
miles an hour.;    <PERSON>Melnick</PERSON> 42 is in a galaxy about 170,000 light-years from
<LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>. A light-year is about 5.8 trillion miles.;    "We couldn't have made
these measurements without the Hubble," Heap said.;    She said the space
telescope's spectrograph will be used to survey stars in a number of galaxies
to learn how stars form in different parts of the heavens.;    "Stars in other
galaxies may form in different ways because the chemistry of the galaxies is
different," she said. "It is like sampling from different cultures.";    <ORGANIZATION>Nino
Panagia of the Space Telescope Science Institute</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Baltimore</LOCATION> said the
Hubble's faint object camera had been able to make the most accurate
measurements of the distance between the <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> and a star outside the Milky
Way galaxy.;    <ORGANIZATION>Panagia</ORGANIZATION> said that by measuring light from different parts of a
ring that has formed around an exploded star called supernova 1987A, he has
been able to determine the distance from <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> at 169,000 light-years. That's
twice as accurate as measurements taken from ground instruments, he said.;   
The work, he said, is the first step toward determining precisely the scale of
the universe. The study will be used to calibrate other measurements taken on
stars deeper and deeper into the universe, <LOCATION>Panagia</LOCATION> said.;    <PERSON>Jeff Hester</PERSON> of
the <ORGANIZATION>California Institute of Technology</ORGANIZATION> said <ORGANIZATION>Hubble</ORGANIZATION>'s wide-field camera had
been used to make unprecedented photos of a star called <LOCATION>Eta Carina</LOCATION> that may be
on the brink of exploding.;    Images collected from the star were processed
through a computer to remove <ORGANIZATION>Hubble</ORGANIZATION>'s focusing flaw, and clearly shows it's
spewing material and is surrounded by a halo-like cloud structure.  </TEXT>
