<HEAD>Hubble Telescope Spots Galaxy That May Have Black Hole</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Tod in 6th graf is cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A photo taken by the <ORGANIZATION>Hubble Space Telescope</ORGANIZATION>
shows a galaxy seen only as fuzzy ball by telescopes on <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> is
actually so tightly packed with stars that it may harbor a black
hole at its center, <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> said <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>.
   The picture, which an official said was taken ``to prove to the
public that the Hubble is not broken,'' shows a galaxy 400 times
more tightly packed with stars than the sun's own Milky Way galaxy.
   Scientists said the Hubble photo captured more detail of the
galaxy than is possible by Earthbound telescopes and was thus able
to determine that the stellar group had many more stars than
expected.
   The picture was taken by the wide field-planetary camera on
Hubble, one of the instruments officials said was seriously
affected by a focusing flaw manufactured into the telescope but not
discovered until after it was launched.
   Officials also released a photo taken with another Hubble camera
that shows a ring of matter encircling a supernova, a star that
exploded in the southern sky in <DATE>1987</DATE>. The ring of material had not
been spotted before by telescopes on <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>.
   <PERSON>Tod R. Lauer</PERSON>, an astronomer with the <ORGANIZATION>National Optical Astronomy
Observatories</ORGANIZATION>, said the compact galaxy of stars discovered by the
Hubble ``is vastly denser than we expected this galaxy to be.''
   He said ground-based photos of the galaxy showed a smooth blob
of light and gave no suggestion that it contained so many stars.
   ``We've never been able to study any galaxy outside of our local
group (two dozen galaxies near the Milky Way) at this resolution
before,'' <PERSON>Lauer</PERSON> said.
   The galaxy, called NGC7457, is 40 million light years away and
contains about 30,000 stars within an area of only about nine light
years.
   Hubble chief scientist <PERSON>Ed Weiler</PERSON> said that one explanation for
such a dense galaxy would be the presence of a black hole.
   ``We're not claiming that this is a black hole,'' he said at a
news conference. ``It is not inconsistent with a black hole,
however.''
   Astronomy theory holds that a black hole can be formed when
stellar matter collects in such a mass of such density and of such
a high gravitational force that even light cannot escape.
   There have been no confirmed black holes found in the universe,
but <PERSON>Weiler</PERSON> said that if one existed it might take on the appearance
of the galaxy photographed by the Hubble.
   <PERSON>Weiler</PERSON> said the galaxy will be further studied by Hubble
instruments to determine if it does contain a black hole.
   The other photo released showed a glowing ring encircling
supernova 1987A, an exploded star 160,000 light years from <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>.
   The picture was taken by <ORGANIZATION>Hubble</ORGANIZATION>'s faint object camera, an
instrument made the <ORGANIZATION>European Space Agency</ORGANIZATION> for the space telescope.
   Nino <LOCATION>Panagia</LOCATION>, a <ORGANIZATION>ESA</ORGANIZATION> scientist, said the photo shows that matter
ejected from the star years before its explosion was compacted and
then set aglow by the burst of light when the star blew up. He said
the ring will be blow apart within a few years when the blast wave
from the exploding collides with the material in the ring.
   <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> took the pictures as part of a campaign to demonstrate that
the Hubble is a valuable telescope even though it has flawed optics.
   <PERSON>Eric Chaisson</PERSON>, educational director of the <ORGANIZATION>Space Telescope
Science Institute</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Baltimore</LOCATION>, said he wrote memos in recent weeks
calling for a campaign to change the perception of the public and
of the science community about the problems with Hubble.
   In a memo obtained by the <LOCATION>San Jose</LOCATION> (<LOCATION>Calif.</LOCATION>) <ORGANIZATION>Mercury News</ORGANIZATION>,
<PERSON>Chaisson</PERSON> said action should be taken to change the public image of
the <MONEY>$1.6 billion</MONEY> observatory.
   ``Unless a dramatic campaign is mounted to share with the
American public the technical truth with a positive spin,''
<PERSON>Chaisson</PERSON> wrote, ``then we should prepare ourselves for an endless
stream of newspaper cartoons, late-night TV talk-show jokes and
blistering post-mortems by columnists the world over.''
   He added: ``We shall continue to see an erosion of public
support for <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION>'s ambitious space program.''
   Reached by telephone, <PERSON>Chaisson</PERSON> confirmed that he had written
such a memo, noting that the pictures of the galaxy and supernova
were taken in part because of his efforts.
   ``We needed some science to prove to the public that Hubble is
not broken,'' he said. ``I don't apologize for it. What I was
trying to do (with the memo) was to jerk the system around so it
would do a little science.''
   Since Hubble has been launched, it has been in a shakedown
operation designed to test it capabilities. Since the focusing flaw
was found, engineers have been operating the Hubble to find out the
precise nature of the malfunction.
   <PERSON>Chaisson</PERSON> said his memo helped persuade <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> to interrupt the
engineering checkout and take some pictures of scientific value.

</TEXT>
