<DESCRIPT>  SPACE; RESEARCH; REPORT  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Scientists have discovered what may be the first known planet outside our
solar system -- a mysterious object, about 10 times the mass of the Earth,
orbiting a dead and distant star.;    The finding by a team of British
astronomers, reported today in the journal Nature, set astronomers buzzing.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  GOOD HEAVENS! ANOTHER PLANET MAY BE OUT THERE,
SCIENTISTS SAY  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     If confirmed, it will challenge fundamental views of how stars and solar
systems evolve, <PERSON>David C. Black</PERSON>, director of the Lunar and <ORGANIZATION>Planetary Institute</ORGANIZATION>
in <LOCATION>Houston</LOCATION>, wrote in an accompanying commentary.;    Evidence for the
existence of the planet is strong, astronomers say, but they are at a loss to
explain how it got there.;    The problem: Its parent star, known as
PSR1829-10, blew up more than a million years ago in a supernova. If the
planet had been around at the time, it probably would have been destroyed or
released from orbit. And no theory exists to explain how it could have formed
in the years since.;    "I'm usually quite skeptical. But I thought this was
quite a strong case," said <PERSON>Douglas Lin</PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION>University of California</ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON>Santa
Cruz</PERSON>, who spent <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> <TIME>afternoon</TIME> debating the new findings with a dozen
colleagues and students. "It is very exciting, very intriguing. We're
discussing various possibilities for how this thing could have formed and how
it could currently exist.";    Detecting planets around other stars is tricky.
If they exist -- and most astronomers now believe they do -- they are
relatively tiny objects lost in the glare of their respective suns, too dim to
see directly with the most powerful telescope.;    Although a number of
scientists claimed to have found indirect evidence of planets over the past
few decades, none of their discoveries has ever been confirmed.;    The latest
report came almost by accident.;    <PERSON>Andrew Lyne</PERSON> and his colleagues at the
<ORGANIZATION>University of Manchester</ORGANIZATION> were surveying a type of neutron star known as a
pulsar. It represents one of the last stages in the life cycle of a star like
our sun, which over millions of years would be expected to expand, explode in
a supernova and contract into a small, dark, extremely dense neutron star.;   
Pulsars are neutron stars that spin rapidly, giving off beams of radio waves
that sweep like beacons across space. Usually these pulses are very regular;
those from PSR1829-10 arrive three times a second. But over the past five
years, the British team noticed that the rate varied slightly, slowing down
and speeding up on a regular six-month cycle.;    The team concluded that
something must be orbiting the pulsar, and that its gravitational attraction
was alternately tugging the pulsar toward and away from <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>. The object
would be about 10 times the mass of the <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> and in a circular orbit, about
as far away from the pulsar as Venus is from the sun. The most reasonable
candidate, members said, would be a planet, and it is possible that longer
observation will reveal more planets around the same pulsar.;    If a planet
is indeed there, <PERSON>Lin</PERSON> said, it most likely would have formed after the
supernova explosion -- perhaps from material ejected in the explosion that
fell back toward the star and whirled into a disk that congealed into chunks
of rock.;    In any case, it is extremely unlikely that such a planet would
harbor life, said <PERSON>Geoffrey Marcy</PERSON>, an astronomer at <ORGANIZATION>San Francisco State
University</ORGANIZATION> who is conducting his own planetary search at <ORGANIZATION>Lick Observatory</ORGANIZATION> on
<LOCATION>Mount Hamilton.</LOCATION>;    "A pulsar is a dead neutron star that's already lived its
life and used up all its nuclear energy," he said. "So prospects for life as
we know it are actually zero, I would say."  </TEXT>
