<HEAD>Astronomers From Virginia and Australia Find What May Be Brown
Dwarf Star</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Astronomers have identified for the first time
what they believe is a brown dwarf star, a stellar body that lacks
the mass to trigger the fusion reaction that gives stars their
brilliant light.
   The <ORGANIZATION>National Science Foundation</ORGANIZATION> announced <DATE>Thursday</DATE> that <PERSON>Philip
A. Ianna</PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION>University of Virginia</ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON>Michael S. Bessell</PERSON> of
the <LOCATION>Stromlo</LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Siding Spring Observatories</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Australia</LOCATION> identified
the candidate brown dwarf after taking measurements of its
brightness and mass.
   Visible only in the skies of the southern hemisphere, the dim,
red stellar body equals about <PERCENT>5 percent</PERCENT> of the mass of the sun. The
sun emits about 4,000 times more light than the dwarf.
   The dwarf is in the <LOCATION>Milky Way</LOCATION>, the galaxy which includes the
sun, and is about 68 light-years away, the astronomers said. A
light-year is the distance light travels in a year, a bit less than
6 trillion miles.
   Brown dwarfs have been theorized to exist for years with most
experts predicting they would have <PERCENT>7 percent</PERCENT> to <PERCENT>8 percent</PERCENT> of the
mass of the sun.
   This would not be sufficient mass for gravitational forces to
compress it and heat it to the point where its hydrogen fuses into
helium. Without fusion, such a stellar body would give off only a
faint red glow caused by its modest gravitational compression.
   Ianna and <PERSON>Bessell</PERSON> said they found the candidate brown dwarf by
studying a group of very, very faint stars first discovered by
<PERSON>Michael R. S. Hawkins</PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION>Royal Observatory</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Edinburgh</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>Scotland</LOCATION>.
   ``We have measured the distance from <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> to what seemed like
the dimmest of these stars and found that the star is truly
faint,'' <PERSON>Ianna</PERSON> said in a statement released by the foundation.
``This supports the hypothesis that this whole group of stars is
faint and contains other brown dwarf candidates.''
   Some astronomers have suggested that brown dwarfs may be the
so-called missing matter of the universe.
   The missing matter question arose when astronomers studying the
movement of stars and galaxies concluded that gravitation forces
acting on visible stellar bodies are too great to be explained by
the mass of the observed objects in space. Some believe that up to
<PERCENT>90 percent</PERCENT> of the matter in the universe is not seen. Brown dwarfs,
it has been proposed, could be part of the undetected matter.
   There is also a theory that the missing mass is cold, dark
matter such as interstellar molecules, black holes and a subatomic
particles called neutrinos, which cannot be observed.
   Ianna and <PERSON>Bessell</PERSON> studied the candidate brown dwarf using an
electronic camera on the one-meter telescope at the <ORGANIZATION>Siding Spring
Observatory</ORGANIZATION>.
   Sighting from two different perspectives within the <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>'s
orbit of the sun, the scientists were able to calculate the
distance of the object from <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>. The mass of the object was
estimated based on studies of its luminosity, or brightness.
</TEXT>
