<LEADPARA>  A vast cloud of gas molecules has been detected near the fringe of the
observable universe, giving astronomers a revealing glimpse into the earliest
stars in the firmament and the creation of galaxies.;   Astronomers reported
in the Astronomical Journal, being published this week, that the cloud had at
least 100 times the mass of the Milky Way galaxy, making it the largest such
object ever observed. And it appears to be the most distant object found to
harbor molecules -- in this case, carbon monoxide.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  SCIENTISTS DISCOVER A GALAXY IN THE MAKING  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     The cloud is estimated to be 12 billion light-years away, 10 times farther
than any other molecular gas cloud seen.;   The two discoverers, <PERSON>Robert Brown</PERSON>
and <PERSON>Paul Vanden Bout</PERSON>, both of the <ORGANIZATION>National Radio Astronomy Observatory</ORGANIZATION> in
<LOCATION>Charlottesville</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Va.</LOCATION>, said the huge volume of gas being detected at such a
great distance was strong evidence that they had observed a galaxy still in
the formation process.;   The cloud is being seen as it existed about 3
billion years after the presumed birth of the universe -- the Big Bang -- and
no galaxy had ever before been caught in the act of forming so relatively
early in cosmic history.;   The observations, they also said, demonstrate that
galaxy formation is preceded by the gravitational accumulation of an enormous
reservoir of molecular gas that occurred surprisingly soon after the <ORGANIZATION>Big
Bang.</ORGANIZATION>;   In an announcement of their discovery, <PERSON>Brown</PERSON> and <PERSON>Vanden Bout</PERSON> said
<DATE>Friday</DATE> that the findings were "in keeping with models of galaxy formation,
never before confirmed, that galaxies form by the gravitational accumulation
of pre-existing clouds of gas."  </TEXT>
