<HL> A Telescope in Space May Get a Nice View Of the Dawn of Time --- But NASA Must First Put It Into Orbit and Keep It From the Fate of a Meteor </HL>
<AUTHOR> Bob Davis (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> GOVMT </CO>
<IN> ARO TEL </IN>
<TEXT>
   Sometime next year, scientists hope to turn on a video screen, butter their popcorn and settle back to watch the dawn of the universe. 

   They won't be seeing a new <PERSON>George Lucas</PERSON> movie but rather the world's first time machine, in orbit around the <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>. 
If everything goes as planned, astronomers will come as close as anyone ever has to viewing the Creation. 

   The scientists won't see the very beginning of time, but they will see stars and galaxies as they existed 14 billion years ago. 
That's how long light from the most distant of those stars takes to reach our planet. 
It's also a scant billion years or so after the big bang -- the monumental explosion of fiery gases that astronomers theorize created the universe and started cosmic clocks ticking. 

   <PERSON>James Westphal</PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION>California Institute of Technology</ORGANIZATION> planetary scientist, expects the time machine, formally called the <ORGANIZATION>Hubble Space Telescope</ORGANIZATION>, to provide many insights. 
"Some of the most intriguing questions for all of us," he says, "are: How did we come to be? 
How did things look after the universe formed? 
How has the universe changed?" 

   In <DATE>June</DATE> of next year, the <ORGANIZATION>National Aeronautics and Space Administration</ORGANIZATION> intends to launch the telescope above the haze of the <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>'s atmosphere. 
From there it will beam back pictures of stars and galaxies that are invisible from the ground. 
Scientists comparing these primordial objects (long since dead perhaps) with younger ones closer to home may be able to trace how the universe has evolved and better predict its future. 
<PERSON>Lennard Fisk</PERSON>, who heads <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION>'s space-science program, calls the telescope project "one of the premier science missions of the century." 

   The success of the scheme will depend, of course, on whether the telescope ever gets into the sky and stays there. 
A frustrated <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> has spent <MONEY>$1.5 billion</MONEY> building the machine and is five years behind schedule in launching it. 
All the telescope has seen so far is the inside of a <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> warehouse, where it piles up storage and maintenance bills of <MONEY>$8 million</MONEY> a month. 
And the eventual launch is fraught with peril. 
<ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> must plan everything very carefully. 
Among possible mishaps: Sunspots could cause the telescope, which weighs 12 tons and is 43 feet long, to plunge to <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> like a meteor. 

   If the space telescope does get going, astronomers promise feats that are worthy of Hollywood-exploring black holes and exploding stars; searching for other life in the universe and gauging the end of time. 

   Astronomers say that the <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>'s fate is sealed. 
Five billion years from now the sun will slowly swallow the <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> in a huge fireball. 
The fate of the universe is still a mystery. 
Astronomers can't tell whether the universe will expand forever, powered by the big bang of old, or whether it will someday collapse into an apocalyptic big crunch. 

   <PERSON>John Huchra</PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION>Harvard University</ORGANIZATION> astronomer, is one of a dozen scientists who plan to spend three years using the space telescope to study the size of the universe and the speed at which it is expanding. 
By comparing the velocity of distant galaxies -- which are many billions of years old -- with that of nearer, younger galaxies, he says, scientists will be able to measure more precisely whether gravity is slowing down the universe until, someday, it will finally implode. 

   "There's a magic number that sets the scale of the universe," <PERSON>Mr. Huchra</PERSON> says. 
"Ever since <DATE>1929</DATE>, people have been trying to figure this out." 
That's when <PERSON>Edwin Hubble</PERSON>, for whom the telescope is named, first tried to calculate how fast the universe is expanding beyond the Milky Way. 

   <PERSON>Riccardo Giacconi</PERSON>, the director of the <ORGANIZATION>Space Telescope Science Institute at Johns Hopkins University</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Baltimore</LOCATION>, has the most ambitious plan of all-searching for life on other planets. 
With the space telescope, he says, "We'll learn more probably if we're alone or if we have company." 

   Ground-based telescopes have never found another solar system like this one, with planets orbiting a sun. 
The brilliance of a star's light is so great and the <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>'s atmosphere is so hazy that astronomers using computer graphics can see only bands of color that ring certain stars. 
Some of the those colors may imply planets; the space telescope, with its great range and clarity of vision, might be able to tell for sure. 

   <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> set up the space-telescope institute to build a computerized map of 20 million stars and to choose plans for stargazing. 
In the institute's basement, astronomers can help point the telescope, videogame-roller-ball style, by rotating a ball from side to side, and examine the exotica of the universe on a video screen receiving transmissions from the telescope. 

   Among the weirdest phenomena scientists plan to hunt for are black holes -- gravitational fields so powerful they crush stars. (<PERSON>Duccio Macchetto</PERSON>, an Italian scientist who has worked on the space telescope for 13 years, believes that a black hole the size of a "fingernail" may have struck the <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> in the early part of the century, leveling a Siberian forest.) 

   Nobody has ever seen a black hole because light can't escape from a black hole's grip. 
But astronomers theorize that odd visible patterns of light and huge jets of matter may be last gasps of stars being pulverized by black holes. 
<PERSON>Albert Boggess</PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> astronomer, says the space telescope could pinpoint brilliant lights in space that may be beacons for black holes but that look fuzzy from <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>. 

   <PERSON>Mr. Westphal</PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION>Cal Tech</ORGANIZATION> scientist who designed the telescope's <MONEY>$53 million</MONEY> camera, wants to aim it at M87, a galaxy 33 million light-years away, which has an enormous blue plume at its center -- black-hole territory, he reckons. 
"You know this black hole is only the size of the moon and it's eaten up a billion stars," he says, giggling at the thought of such gluttony. 

   Other scientists involved in the telescope project will dabble in cosmic archaeology -- comparing ancient galaxies on the rim of the universe with newer, closer ones to see how galaxies develop. 
<PERSON>John Bahcall</PERSON>, an astrophysicist at the <ORGANIZATION>Institute for Advanced Study</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Princeton</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>N.J.</LOCATION>, suspects that quasars -- the most luminous objects in the sky -- are the "birth pangs or death throes" of galaxies. 
<PERSON>Mr. Westphal</PERSON> believes that galaxies grow like fish, swallowing stars and smaller galaxies as they move about, and getting bigger over time. 

   <PERSON>Richard Harms</PERSON>, who developed a space-telescope instrument to detect faint objects, will track supernova-exploding stars -- to see how quickly they decay and thereby gauge the speed of the universe. 
One likely target: the Magellanic clouds, 163,000 light-years away, which last year featured the brightest supernova seen from <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> in 383 years. 
"We'll rush to look at new ones as soon as they go off," <PERSON>Mr. Harms</PERSON> promises. 

   Before any of this neat stuff begins, however, <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> must get the space telescope into orbit on the space shuttle -- and keep it in orbit. 
All sorts of things have gone awry for the space telescope since <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> started working on it in <DATE>1977</DATE>, but the biggest blow was the Challenger tragedy, which delayed the launch three years, to <DATE>June 1989</DATE>. 
And next <DATE>summer</DATE> may be an awful time to try to bring it off. 
Astronomers predict that will be near the height of the sunspot cycle, when exploding gases on the surface of the sun will push the <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>'s atmosphere deeper into space -- and threaten to drag the telescope to <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> in a flaming wreck. 

   If the sunspots are as explosive as is feared, <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> will face the following difficult choice: launch the telescope so high above the atmosphere that a shuttle may not be able to reach it again for repair, or launch it low enough so subsequent shuttles can retrieve it and boost it higher every six months or so -- at a cost of about <MONEY>$300 million</MONEY> a nudge. 

   A "tiger team" of solar experts will advise <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON>James Moore</PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> spacetelescope official, says the agency will delay the launch if sending it up on schedule means that it will then have to re-boost the telescope even once a year. 
And <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON>Mr. Fisk</PERSON> vows: "One decision I don't plan to make is putting the space telescope too low and having it follow me home." 

</TEXT>
