<FIRST>u a AM-KeckTelescope     12-04 0581</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Keck Telescope,0698</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Photo from Massive New Hawaii Telescope Revealed</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists on <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> displayed the
first picture taken by what will soon be the world's most powerful
optical telescope, a huge instrument designed to peer deeper into
space than ever before.
   When it is completed, the <MONEY>$94.2 million</MONEY> <ORGANIZATION>Keck Telescope</ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION>Mauna
Kea</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Hawaii</LOCATION>, will be the world's largest, with a mirror 10 meters
in diameter. It also is the first to be built of automated mirror
segments.
   Astronomers say the <PERSON>Keck</PERSON> will enable them to gaze back 12
billion years in time by revealing light images still traveling
toward <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>.
   ``These are really time machines, given the finite speed of
light,'' said <PERSON>Edward Stone</PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION>California Association
of Research</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Astronomy</LOCATION>, composed of scientists from the
<ORGANIZATION>California Institute of Technology</ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION>University of
California</ORGANIZATION>.
   The photo of galaxy <ORGANIZATION>NGC</ORGANIZATION> 1232, taken with only a quarter of the
<PERSON>Keck</PERSON>'s 36 mirror segments in place, more than matched the quality
of images from the world's largest effective telescope, the 5-meter
<ORGANIZATION>Hale Telescope</ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION>Palomar Observatory</ORGANIZATION>.
   The image was taken <DATE>Nov. 24</DATE> from the <ORGANIZATION>W.M. Keck Observatory on
Mauna Kea</ORGANIZATION>, a 13,796-foot volcano on the island of <LOCATION>Hawaii</LOCATION>.
   The picture of the galaxy, 65 million light years from <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> in
the constellation Eridanus, marks the telescope's ``first light,''
a term astronomers use to describe the first viewing through a new
telescope.
   The photo has no particular scientific value; <ORGANIZATION>NGC</ORGANIZATION> 1232 was
selected simply to demonstrate the optical quality of the
telescope, said mirror designer <PERSON>Jerry Nelson</PERSON>, an astronomer at the
<ORGANIZATION>University of California</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Berkeley</LOCATION>.
   ``When we first saw the picture we were really thrilled,'' said
<PERSON>Nelson</PERSON>. ``We were all hopping up and down.''
   The telescope won't be fully functioning until late next year,
with all mirror segments in place and precision cameras mounted to
record the images it returns.
   When it is completed, the <ORGANIZATION>Keck Telescope</ORGANIZATION> is expected to be twice
as powerful as the <PERSON>Hale</PERSON> and far more accurate and reliable than a
6-meter Soviet telescope that is frequently inoperable.
   The <PERSON>Keck</PERSON> differs from other large telescopes in that its mirror
is made up of separate hexagonal mirror segments 6 feet in
diameter. The aluminum-coated mirrors are kept in alignment within
1-millionth of an inch by computer-controlled sensors.
   Stone said a single-piece 10-meter-wide mirror probably could
not be constructed with existing technology.
   The telescope will offer research opportunities not possible
with the <ORGANIZATION>Hubble Space Telescope</ORGANIZATION>, launched earlier this year by a
space shuttle. Because it orbits <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> above the distorting effects
of the atmosphere, the <MONEY>$1.5 billion</MONEY> <ORGANIZATION>Hubble Space Telescope</ORGANIZATION> was
supposed to see farther into the universe than the <PERSON>Keck</PERSON>, even
though the <ORGANIZATION>Hubble</ORGANIZATION> has a smaller mirror.
   <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> discovered after it was launched that the Hubble's mirror
was flawed during construction, rendering it less powerful than
planned until a space shuttle crew can fix it in <DATE>1993</DATE>.
   However, the <PERSON>Keck</PERSON>, with its large, light-gathering mirror, will
be a better instrument for analyzing the light spectrums of stars.
Stone said this will enable scientists to better understand the
nature of the stars and calculate their speed.
   By providing images that reach back 12 billion years, scientists
will see stars as they appeared some 3 billion years after the
birth of the universe. Palomar, by contrast, reaches back only 8
billion years.
   Caltech and the <ORGANIZATION>University of California</ORGANIZATION> are sharing the cost of
the telescope. Caltech, aided by a <MONEY>$70 million</MONEY> grant from the <ORGANIZATION>W.M.
Keck Foundation</ORGANIZATION>, put up the <MONEY>$87 million</MONEY> the project originally was
expected to cost. Overruns of <MONEY>$7.2 million</MONEY> will be shared by the
two universities, and UC will pay the annual operating cost of
about <MONEY>$3 million</MONEY>, <ORGANIZATION>Stone</ORGANIZATION> said.
   <PERSON>Nelson</PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION>Mauna Kea</ORGANIZATION> is considered the world's best site for a
telescope because its high altitude reduces atmospheric
distortions. But the thin air often impairs researchers' thinking
ability and causes severe headaches, he said. As a result,
operations must be carefully planned and monitored by the project's
sea-level headquarters.
