<CAPTION>  Drawing; DRAWING: National Aeronautics and Space Adminstration; WANTED -- This
drawing of the stratospheric observatory for far-infrared astronomy shows a
100-inch telescope on the left, measuring instruments in the center and a
data-reading control panel to the right.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  US; SPACE; TRAVEL; OFFICE; RESEARCH; PROGRAM; COST  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  THE NATION'S top astronomers proposed a $3 billion wish list Tuesday,
including a project dear to NASA/Ames Research Center in Mountain View: an
airborne telescope, mounted on a Boeing 747, that would explore barely visible
galaxies and seek data to explain how stars form.;    Once every 10 years, the
National Research Council surveys astronomers and culls their ideas to find
the best, most efficient science. From hundreds of suggestions, 15 made the
cut this time. Half to two-thirds are expected to get federal funding for the
next decade, and the rest will get strong consideration from Congress.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  ASTRONOMERS REVEAL WISH LIST
FUNDING SOUGHT FOR 15 PROJECTS, INCLUDING
AMES' FLYING TELESCOPE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  See also related story on this page.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Key congressional leaders, such as the chairman of the <ORGANIZATION>House Science, Space
and Technology Committee</ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON>George Brown Jr.</PERSON>, D-Riverside, heard the council's
recommendations.;    One of the strongest was a renewed effort to maintain and
upgrade existing observatories.;    "No prudent businessman would run a
business with such a small investment in infrastructure," said <PERSON>John Bahcall</PERSON>,
of the <ORGANIZATION>Institute for Advanced Study</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Princeton</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>N.J.</LOCATION>, who helped write the
report.;     THE PROPOSED list includes some expensive items, such as the <MONEY>$1.3
billion</MONEY> space infrared telescope facility, a cousin of the Hubble space
telescope planned by the <ORGANIZATION>Jet Propulsion Laboratory</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Pasadena</LOCATION>. It also
includes <MONEY>$250 million</MONEY> for smaller, shoestring projects.;    "We felt that 'big
science' is very important," said <PERSON>Christopher McKee</PERSON>, an astrophysicist at the
<ORGANIZATION>University of California</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Berkeley</LOCATION>, who worked on the report. "And we want to
encourage 'small science.' We don't view it as an either/or situation.";   
The Ames project falls somewhere in between, in a category called "moderate
programs.";    The <MONEY>$230 million</MONEY> stratospheric observatory for far-infrared
astronomy, in the works since <DATE>1986</DATE>, is a joint project of the <ORGANIZATION>National
Aeronautics and Space Administration</ORGANIZATION> and the German federal space agency.;   
<ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> would develop and operate the plane, while the Germans have agreed to
finance and build the telescope.;    KNOWN AS <LOCATION>SOFIA</LOCATION>, the 747 would carry a
100-inch-diameter telescope. It would collect about 10 times more light than
the smaller, older model Ames now flies in a Lockheed C-141, which is called
the Kuiper airborne observatory.;    The Kuiper is the world's only flying
telescope. <LOCATION>SOFIA</LOCATION> would replace it. About <MONEY>$6 million</MONEY> has been spent already on
<LOCATION>SOFIA</LOCATION>, which is scheduled for funding in <DATE>1993</DATE> and takeoff in <DATE>1998.</DATE>;    Flying
45,000 feet above <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>, several thousand feet higher than the average
passenger jet, <LOCATION>SOFIA</LOCATION> will focus on a key part of the electromagnetic spectrum
-- the infrared, which lies between shorter visible light and longer radio
waves.;    Water in the <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>'s atmosphere absorbs much of the infrared
spectrum, making the waves undetectable to ground telescopes.;    The infrared
spectrum holds clues to cradles of stars called molecular clouds. Scientists
believe the cold, dark, gaseous clouds, which are mostly hydrogen, give birth
to stars. But they don't know exactly how.;    <LOCATION>SOFIA</LOCATION> will be able to look at
clouds both inside and outside the Milky Way galaxy.;    THE SCIENCE will be
great, said <PERSON>Ed Erickson</PERSON>, <LOCATION>SOFIA</LOCATION>'s chief scientist. But he also raved about the
observatory's adaptability. After flights, researchers will be able to change
and improve the scientific gadgetry on board the plane. That is something
scientists can't do with the Hubble telescope, for instance, which is loaded
with outdated technology.;    "They can conceive of an instrument, build it
and fly it, in a few years or less," said <PERSON>Erickson</PERSON>, who flew in one of the
original flying telescopes, a Learjet first launched by Ames 25 years ago. He
believes that cutting-edge technology can be put into <LOCATION>SOFIA</LOCATION> for its entire
20-year lifespan.;    <PERSON>Erickson</PERSON> said <LOCATION>SOFIA</LOCATION> would complement the space infrared
telescope facility, which is planned to have a smaller, more sensitive
telescope. The space-based telescope would be able to answer more questions
about cosmology -- the origin of the universe.;    Another program the
research council deemed essential was the millimeter array, a <MONEY>$115 million</MONEY> set
of telescopes planned by the <ORGANIZATION>National Radio Astronomy Observatory</ORGANIZATION>. It owes
some of its technology to a three-telescope array run by <ORGANIZATION>UC-Berkeley</ORGANIZATION> in a lava
bed between <LOCATION>Mount Shasta</LOCATION> and Mount Lassen.;    "It will be enormously
significant," said <PERSON>James R. Forster</PERSON>, an astronomer at the <LOCATION>Berkeley</LOCATION> post, who
predicted that the millimeter array would be used to study molecular clouds in
the radio spectrum. "Resolution will be improved, and we'll get finer images."  </TEXT>
