<LEADPARA>  An orbiting observatory has upset existing astronomical theory by detecting
violent bursts of gamma rays in space that could not have been produced by any
known object or phenomenon in the cosmos.;   Astrophysicists who announced the
finding Monday said the mysterious signals could be coming from "exotic small
objects" very near the solar system or from extremely powerful objects lurking
at the edges of the universe.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  VIOLENT GAMMA RAY BURSTS JETTISON SPACE THEORIES  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Fleeting but powerful barrages of gamma rays have posed one of the most
enduring and unusual mysteries of modern astronomy since they were detected
more than two decades ago. But until the new discovery, scientists thought
they could explain their origin through known phenomena.;   The findings --
from <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION>'s massive <ORGANIZATION>Gamma Ray Observatory</ORGANIZATION>, launched into <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> orbit less than
six months ago -- indicate that the sources of the bright bursts could be very
close objects with relatively modest firepower, or that they could be
enormously distant cataclysms that release far more energy in one second than
the stellar explosions known as supernovae.;   Either way, their existence
shakes current theories on what's out there, according to elated <ORGANIZATION>National
Aeronautics and Space Administration</ORGANIZATION> scientists.;   The observations cannot be
explained by any existing theory or object, said <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> scientist <PERSON>Gerald
Fishman</PERSON>, leader of the team whose instrument made the discovery. The sources
"must be a new type of object previously unknown or undetectable" in other
wavelengths.;   News of the discovery was greeted by scientists outside the
<ORGANIZATION>Gamma Ray Observatory</ORGANIZATION> team as "astounding" and "mind-blowing." Theoretical
astrophysicists are expected to scramble to find some explanation for the
findings.;   Astrophysicists had grown comfortable with the theory that the
bursts -- 100,000 times as luminous as the sun but invisible to the eye
because of their wavelength -- originated in explosions or "star quakes" on
the surfaces of neutron stars within our own Milky Way galaxy. (Neutron stars
are ordinary stars that have collapsed, compressing matter with the mass of
the sun into an object about the size of a metropolitan area, giving off
gargantuan amounts of energy.);   But if that theory is true, as recent
observations using the Soviet spacecraft GRANAT seem to confirm, the <ORGANIZATION>Gamma Ray
Observatory</ORGANIZATION>'s detector would have shown most of the bursts coming from the
center of the Milky Way galaxy's disk -- a flattened pinwheel of stars with
<LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> and the solar system located toward the end of one of the arms. This
region is rich in neutron stars. So are other galaxies, but the neutron stars
are not numerous enough or distributed in a way that accounts for the gamma
ray bursts.;   The new evidence indicates the gamma ray bursts are not
emanating from the neutron stars at the galactic center but rather from all
directions.;   This means they have to be either very close, like a cloud of
unknown objects enclosing the solar system, or enormously distant, scientists
said. All the objects at intermediate distances, in galaxies or galactic
clusters, appear in clumps and chains rather than in a uniform distribution.; 
 Gamma ray theorist <PERSON>Paul Joss</PERSON>, a physics professor at the <ORGANIZATION>Massachusetts
Institute of Technology</ORGANIZATION>, said the discovery will have a "very dramatic effect"
in the science community. "I am at a total loss to explain the findings.";  
The possibilities, he said, are that the gamma rays are coming from objects as
diverse as the theoretical "cosmic strings" on the edges of the universe to
invisible dead stars lurking "virtually in our back yard." Or the mystery may
turn out to be connected with another of astronomy's puzzles, he said. That
is, it may be linked to the vast amount of theoretical "dark matter" that so
far has been detected only in the gravitational force it exerts on visible
objects throughout the universe.;   Gamma rays, born deep inside atomic
nuclei, are difficult to study. They carry the hottest, highest energies of
any form of electromagnetic radiation and are thought to originate often in
the cataclysms that erupt around some of the most bizarre objects known,
including quasars, pulsars and black holes. But at close range these objects
are not distributed evenly in all directions from <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>. And from the edge of
the universe -- where they might be evenly distributed -- none can produce the
energy levels that reach Earth.;   The 17-ton, <MONEY>$560 million</MONEY> <ORGANIZATION>Gamma Ray
Observatory</ORGANIZATION> is by far the most sensitive and advanced gamma ray hunter ever
dispatched.;   The bursts of gamma rays that it has detected last from a
fraction of a second to hundreds of seconds.  </TEXT>
