bursts -- 100,000 times as luminous as the sun but invisible to the eye
because of their wavelength -- originated in explosions or "starquakes" on the
surfaces of neutron stars within our own Milky Way galaxy. (Neutron stars are
ordinary stars that have collapsed, compressing matter with the mass of the
sun into an object about the size of a metropolitan area, giving off
gargantuan amounts of energy.);   Neutron theory flaws;   But if that theory
were true, as recent observations using the Soviet spacecraft GRANAT seemed to
confirm, the <ORGANIZATION>Gamma Ray Observatory</ORGANIZATION>'s detector would have shown most of the
bursts coming from the center of the Milky Way galaxy's disk -- a flattened
pinwheel of stars with <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> and the solar system located toward the end of
one of the arms. This region is rich in neutron stars. So are other galaxies,
but the neutron stars are not numerous enough or distributed in a way that
accounts for the gamma ray bursts.;   The new evidence indicates the gamma ray
bursts are not emanating from the neutron stars at the galactic center but
rather from all directions.;   This means they have to be either very close,
like a cloud of unknown objects enclosing the solar system, or enormously
distant, scientists said. All the objects at intermediate distances, in
galaxies or galactic clusters, appear in clumps and chains rather than in a
uniform distribution.;   Gamma ray theorist <PERSON>Paul Joss</PERSON>, a physics professor at
the <ORGANIZATION>Massachusetts Institute of Technology</ORGANIZATION>, said the discovery will have a
"very dramatic effect" in the science community. "I am at a total loss to
explain the findings.";   The possibilities, he said, are that the gamma rays
are coming from objects as diverse as the theoretical "cosmic strings" on the
edges of the universe to invisible dead stars lurking "virtually in our back
yard." Or the mystery may turn out to be connected with another of astronomy's
puzzles, he said. That is, it may be linked to the vast amount of theoretical
"dark matter" that so far has been detected only in the gravitational force it
exerts on visible objects throughout the universe.;   Rays hard to study;
Gamma rays, born deep inside atomic nuclei, are difficult to study. They carry
the hottest, highest energies of any form of electromagnetic radiation and are
thought to originate often in the cataclysms that erupt around some of the
most bizarre objects known, including quasars, pulsars and black holes. But at
close range these objects are not distributed evenly in all directions from
<LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>. And from the edge of the universe -- where they might be evenly
distributed -- none can produce the energy levels that reach Earth.;   The
17-ton, <MONEY>$560 million</MONEY> <ORGANIZATION>Gamma Ray Observatory</ORGANIZATION> is by far the most sensitive and
advanced gamma ray hunter ever dispatched.;   The bursts of gamma rays that it
has detected last from a fraction of a second to hundreds of seconds.  </TEXT>
