<HEAD>Mount Wilson Telescope Given New Life</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the nation's oldest astronomical
treasures, the mothballed 100-inch telescope at the <ORGANIZATION>Mount Wilson
Observatory</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>, will be recommissioned under a new
ownership plan for the facility, the <ORGANIZATION>Carnegie Institution</ORGANIZATION> announced
<DATE>Thursday</DATE>.
   The institution, which built the observatory in <DATE>1904</DATE> and has
operated it since, retired the big <PERSON>Hooker</PERSON> telescope in <DATE>1985</DATE> as it
shifted its priorities to development of more powerful instruments
at its new observatory in <LOCATION>Las Campanas</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION>.
   For three decades, the <PERSON>Hooker</PERSON> telescope, completed in <DATE>1917</DATE>, was
the world's largest, and the prototype for all modern-day reflecting
telescopes. Its 100-inch mirror, weighing 4{ tons, was cast by a
French bottle-making company.
   Despite mothballing the <PERSON>Hooker</PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION>Carnegie Institution</ORGANIZATION> has
continued to operate three other research telescopes at <LOCATION>Mount
Wilson</LOCATION>. Under the plan announced <DATE>Thursday</DATE>, the entire observatory
will be transferred to the new Mount Wilson Institution, headed by
<ORGANIZATION>Carnegie</ORGANIZATION> veterans, over the <DATE>next two years</DATE> and will be independently
financed, largely from government grants.
   The arrangement was worked out primarily by <PERSON>George Preston</PERSON>,
former observatory director and now a chief scientist there. Preston
called the plan ``a rebirth for the observatory, and one that will
make the best use of the facilities.''
   Not only will the <PERSON>Hooker</PERSON> telescope be recommissioned within a
year, he said, but it will be fitted with high-tech computer
controls and instruments over two to three years. He said also that
overall research at the observatory will be expanded under plans to
double the operating budget, to <MONEY>$750,000</MONEY>, and to add several more
scientists to the five teams already at work there.
   During the <DATE>1920s</DATE>, <ORGANIZATION>Carnegie</ORGANIZATION> astronomers <PERSON>Edwin Hubble</PERSON> and <PERSON>Milton
Humason</PERSON>, using the <PERSON>Hooker</PERSON> telescope, established that the ``spiral
nebulae'' in the <TIME>night</TIME> sky were other galaxies, made up of billions
of stars and located far outside the Milky Way, the galaxy that
contains the <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>. Thus, the size of the universe then known by
astronomers expanded almost a thousand-fold overnight.
   But growing light pollution from nearby <LOCATION>Los Angeles</LOCATION> has in recent
years virtually destroyed <PERSON>Hooker</PERSON>'s biggest claim to fame _ that
ability to study faint, distant galaxies _ and was a major factor in
<LOCATION>Carnegie</LOCATION>'s decision to focus its efforts in <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION>.
   However, <PERSON>Preston</PERSON> and <PERSON>Arthur Vaughn</PERSON> said the <PERSON>Hooker</PERSON> telescope, at
5,700 feet altitude, remains an ideal tool for studying the sun and
for detecting planets around stars in the Milky Way. It also will be
used to study ``starspots,'' similar to the sunspot activity once
thought to be unique to the sun.
</TEXT>
