<DESCRIPT>  RADIO; REACTION; SCIENCE; PROFESSIONAL  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  A source of fluctuating radio-frequency emissions that suddenly appeared near
the center of our own Milky Way galaxy has astronomers baffled.;    "It's a
real puzzle. But that's why astronomy's fun," said Miller Goss, director of
the Very Large Array (VLA) radio telescope, west of Socorro, N.M.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  RADIO EMISSIONS BAFFLE ASTRONOMERS
MYSTERIOUS FLUCTUATING WAVES FOUND AT MILKY
WAY'S CENTER  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     "The thing that makes it so interesting is it's varying in time in a rather
unusual way," said <PERSON>Marcus Price</PERSON>, professor of physics and astronomy at the
<ORGANIZATION>University of New Mexico.</ORGANIZATION>;    "In astronomy, we expect to have things vary
slowly, with the exception of pulsars. This has been especially true in radio
sources. We have not found them to vary a great deal in short times. This
source seems to vary sharply on a rather short scale," he said.;    The
mystery source has not been detected either optically or in infrared
wavelengths because it is obscured by galactic dust clouds.;    Astronomers
have ruled out possibilities of a supernova -- an exploding star -- or
recurring nova, which is re-energized by matter pulled in from a companion
star.;    The source's radio emission appears to be caused by electrons moving
in a strong magnetic field, <LOCATION>VLA</LOCATION> scientists said.;    <PERSON>Yervant Terzian</PERSON>, chairman
of <ORGANIZATION>Cornell University</ORGANIZATION>'s astronomy department, said he had not yet heard of the
discovery but said, "Some of the most mysterious places in the universe are
the centers of galaxies.";    The enigmatic source was first noticed <DATE>March 11</DATE>
by <PERSON>Jun-Hui Zhao</PERSON>, an astronomer from <LOCATION>Beijing</LOCATION> conducting postdoctoral studies at
the <ORGANIZATION>VLA</ORGANIZATION>.  </TEXT>
