<DESCRIPT>  SPACE; RESEARCH  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  New satellite studies suggest that large clusters of galaxies were formed very
early in time, a finding that threatens fundamental theories about the
evolution of the universe, astronomers said Tuesday.;    A survey of the
heavens by an international X-ray satellite called Rosat has found what may be
large arrays of galaxies centered on quasars about 10 billion light-years away.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  SATELLITE STUDIES FIND GALAXIES FORMED EARLIER
THAN BELIEVED  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Since such vast distances in space also can be a measure of time, the
finding places the clusters at a point only a few billion years later than the
"big bang" that many theorists say started the universe.;    Rosat scientist
<PERSON>Gunther Hasinger</PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION>Max Planck Institute</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Germany</LOCATION> said the satellite
detected "what may be the first glimpse of the structure of the universe" at
such an early point.;    He said the satellite detected many quasars, which
are energy points at the center of some galaxies, in vast clustered groups.;  
 "The quasars may not be distributed randomly, but are in structures,"
<PERSON>Hasinger</PERSON> said at a meeting of the <ORGANIZATION>American Astronomical Society</ORGANIZATION>. "The mere
existence of such structures (at this distance) is not compatible to some
theories.";    Discovery of the quasar groups adds to early findings of
immense clusters of galaxies, each with billions of stars, including one
structure called the "great wall" that extends for about 500 million light
years across.;    Additionally, the journal Nature last week reported that the
<ORGANIZATION>Infrared Astronomy Satellite</ORGANIZATION> has found superclusters on a very large scale.;  
 Scientists attending the society meeting said that the discovery of
structures doesn't destroy the big-bang theory but that it creates great
difficulties for sub-theories that have developed to support the big bang.;   
First published in <DATE>1927</DATE>, the big bang posits that the universe began when a
superdense conglomerate exploded about 10 billion to 20 billion years ago.
Since that instant, all matter has been expanding in all directions, like
shrapnel from an exploded bomb.;    Though many observations have supported
the basic big-bang theory, science has yet to reach a consensus on how matter
expanding from the bang was able to clump together and form first stars, then
galaxies, then clusters and finally the vast groups such as the great wall.  </TEXT>
