<HEAD>Australia Unveils New Telescope To Search Southern Skies</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to DELETE extraneous word ``goes''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER O'LOUGHLIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CULGOORA, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first big radio telescope array
in the <LOCATION>Southern Hemisphere</LOCATION> began operating <DATE>Friday</DATE>, opening a new
window on the little-explored southern sky.
   ``We'll be looking at the center of our galaxy because it passes
right above our head in the <LOCATION>Southern Hemisphere</LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON>Dr. Ron
Ekers</PERSON>, the director of the instrument named the <LOCATION>Australia
Telescope</LOCATION>. ``Much of the galaxy and the nearest neighboring galaxy,
the <ORGANIZATION>Magellanic Cloud</ORGANIZATION> is not visible to observatories in the
<LOCATION>Northern Hemisphere</LOCATION>.''
   Ekers, who for seven years was director of the 27-dish, <ORGANIZATION>Very
Large Array</ORGANIZATION> radio telescope in western <LOCATION>New Mexico</LOCATION>, said the
telescope will study black holes and pulsars.
   The new <MONEY>$40 million</MONEY> instrument located on the windswept plains
of western <LOCATION>New South Wales</LOCATION>, consists of five new 72.6-foot dishes
mounted on 1.86 miles of railroad track.
   An identical dish on a track 1.86 miles away will make the array
equivalent to one dish with a diameter 3.72 miles.
   When linked to the exisiting 211-foot-dish at Parkes 241 miles
to the south and others spread across the continent, the <LOCATION>Australia</LOCATION>
Telescope can be extended like a zoom lens on a camera, to the
equivalent of a dish 2,400 miles in diameter.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Commonwealth Scientific and Industrial Organization</ORGANIZATION>, the
government- funded research institution that designed the
telescope, said the compact array of seven telescopes had an
equivalent resolution to being able to read a telephone directory
at a distance of 660 feet.
   When linked to telescopes in space, it would be 10,000 times
greater.
   ``The <LOCATION>Australia Telescope</LOCATION> is the state of the art in
astronomical technology, it is one of the best telescopes in the
world,'' Prime Minister <PERSON>Bob Hawke</PERSON> told an audience of astronomers
and scientists at the inaugural ceremony.
   Harry Van der Laan, head of the <ORGANIZATION>European Southern Observatory</ORGANIZATION> in
<LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION>, said: ``If <LOCATION>Australia</LOCATION> hadn't built it, the <ORGANIZATION>European Southern
Observatory</ORGANIZATION> would have had to do it in <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION>.''
   ``We have the biggest optical telescopes in the <LOCATION>Southern
Hemisphere</LOCATION> at <ORGANIZATION>La Silla</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION>, but we had no major radio
telescope array. World astronomy cannot do without it,'' he said.
   ``This fills that gap and it puts <LOCATION>Australia</LOCATION> back in the top
league of astronomy. Its the equivalent of winning the <LOCATION>America</LOCATION>'s
Cup in yachting,'' Van der Laan said.
